# The Rise of Electric Vehicles in India: History, Problems, and the Road Ahead (2024–2026)

**Author:** Vivek Kumar  
**Date:** June 2026  
**Type:** Research Document  

---

## Introduction

When I first started looking at Electric Vehicles in March 2024 for a university survey, the conversation around EVs in India felt optimistic — almost euphoric. Government targets were ambitious, startup founders were talking about India becoming a global EV hub, and sales numbers were climbing. Two years later, the picture is more honest. EVs are growing, yes. But they are also catching fire — literally and figuratively.

This document covers the full arc: where India's EV story started, what went wrong, what is going right, and what the future actually looks like based on data available as of June 2026.

---

## Part 1 — The Beginning: Why EVs Became a Priority in India

India is the third largest greenhouse gas emitter in the world. The transportation sector alone accounts for over 13% of the country's energy-related greenhouse gas emissions. In cities like Delhi, vehicular pollution contributes to nearly 19% of PM10 and 39% of PM2.5 particulate matter — the kind that causes respiratory disease, cardiovascular problems, and early death.

Delhi has some of the worst air quality of any major city on earth. By the early 2010s, it was clear that the existing approach — pushing CNG buses, tightening emission norms — was not enough. Vehicle ownership was rising too fast. Between 2020 and 2024, India's EV adoption rate jumped from 0.7% of total motor vehicle sales to 6.3%. That shift was not accidental. It was pushed by policy.

The FAME I and FAME II schemes (Faster Adoption and Manufacturing of Hybrid and Electric Vehicles) laid the groundwork, providing subsidies to EV buyers and incentives for manufacturers. The PM E-Drive scheme followed, targeting charging infrastructure and public transit electrification. Delhi's own EV Policy 2020 set an ambitious target: 25% of all new vehicle registrations to be electric by 2024.

India set a national goal to reach 30% EV penetration in private cars, 70% in commercial vehicles, 40% in buses, and 80% in two- and three-wheelers by 2030.

