## Part 2 — The Early Problems: When Technology Was Not Ready

### 2.1 The Software and Safety Crisis (2021–2023)

The most visible failure of India's early EV push was the scooter fire crisis of 2022. Multiple electric scooters, including models from Ola Electric, Okinawa, and Pure EV, caught fire across the country. In one incident in Nashik, a father and daughter died when their e-bike went up in flames. The government launched an investigation, and the findings pointed to faulty battery cells and poorly designed battery management systems.

In Ola's case specifically, the federal probe found that battery cells and the battery management system were both problematic. The company had launched its S1 and S1 Pro models in August 2021 to massive excitement — 100,000 orders in 24 hours. By December 2021, when deliveries began, the complaints started.

Ola Electric's problems went far beyond fires. Customers reported:
- Vehicles sold with manufacturing defects
- Software glitches in the hub motor
- Battery discharging during periods of non-use
- Service centers overwhelmed with backlogs — HSBC analysts visiting centers across India in 2024 reported most appeared completely overwhelmed
- Overcharging during free service periods
- Warranty claims being denied without explanation

Between September 2023 and August 2024, the Central Consumer Protection Authority (CCPA) received over 10,644 complaints against Ola Electric alone. The National Consumer Helpline was receiving approximately 80,000 complaints per month from Ola customers. In October 2024, the CCPA issued a show cause notice to Ola Electric citing violations of the Consumer Protection Act, including misleading advertisements and unfair trade practices.

The market responded accordingly. Ola Electric's annual sales fell 51% year-on-year in 2025. In 2024, they were the top-selling e-scooter brand in India. By 2025, they had dropped to fourth place, behind TVS Motor, Bajaj Auto, and Ather Energy.

This is important context. When people in our 2024 survey said they were worried about EV technology reliability, they were not being irrational. The technology was genuinely unreliable.

### 2.2 The Charging Infrastructure Problem (Then and Now)

In our 2024 survey, 45.1% of respondents cited poor EV infrastructure as a reason people do not buy personal EVs. That concern has aged well.

As of early 2026, India has approximately 29,000 public charging stations across the country — up from about 5,000 in 2022, which sounds impressive until you consider that 2.3 million EVs were registered in 2025 alone. The ratio works out to roughly one public charger for every 235 EVs on the road. The global benchmark is one charger for every 6 to 20 EVs.

Delhi's situation is stark. The city currently has 8,849 charging points against an official requirement of 36,150. That is a deficit of over 27,000 charging points — in the capital city, which is supposed to be a model for the rest of the country. Battery swapping stations are at 893 against a requirement of 1,500.

And of the chargers that do exist, approximately 18% were non-functional as of March 2026. Some networks have reported non-functional rates as high as 60%. The reasons range from grid voltage issues to poor maintenance to payment system failures.

The Delhi government has announced plans to add 7,000 charging points in 2026 and is targeting over 16,000 total charging points by December 2026. The Delhi EV Policy 2026, released in April 2026, allocates Rs. 3,954 crore toward purchase incentives, infrastructure, and fleet electrification. These are serious commitments. Whether they are executed on time is a different question.

### 2.3 Battery Degradation: The Problem People Are Now Discovering

This is the problem my 2024 survey did not specifically capture, because it was not yet widely discussed. Battery degradation — the gradual reduction in a battery's capacity to hold charge — is becoming a real issue for early EV adopters in India.

India's climate is harsh on lithium-ion batteries. High summer temperatures in Delhi regularly exceed 45°C, which accelerates chemical degradation inside battery cells. Poor thermal management systems in budget EVs make this worse. Users in Delhi and other hot cities report noticing significant range reduction after two to three years of ownership.

Battery replacement is expensive. A replacement battery pack for a popular electric scooter can cost anywhere from Rs. 30,000 to Rs. 80,000 — sometimes more than 30-40% of the vehicle's original price. Warranty coverage is inconsistent and often disputed by manufacturers.

This is currently one of the biggest hidden barriers to EV adoption that surveys and sales data do not capture. People are reluctant to buy a second EV — or recommend one — after experiencing battery degradation in their first.

