## Part 3 — What Is Actually Working

Despite the problems, the EV story in India is not all negative. Some things are genuinely working.

### 3.1 Sales Growth Is Real

India's total EV sales reached 22.7 lakh units in 2025, representing 16.3% year-on-year growth. From June 2025 to May 2026, 27.03 lakh EVs were sold — the highest 12-month total in the country's history. In March 2026, monthly EV sales hit a record of 2,80,093 units.

Electric four-wheelers grew 76.9% in 2025. Electric three-wheelers — autorickshaws and goods carriers — are the quiet success story of Indian EV adoption. E-rickshaws are transforming last-mile connectivity in tier-2 and tier-3 cities without requiring the charging infrastructure that four-wheelers need, because most operators charge overnight at home.

The market leader in electric four-wheelers is Tata Motors with over 42% market share. Unlike Ola, Tata's approach has been slower and more deliberate — investing in service network before scaling sales.

### 3.2 Environmental Impact: Real but Nuanced

Between 2020 and 2024, India's EV adoption prevented an estimated 10 million tonnes of carbon emissions. That is a meaningful number.

However, it is important to be honest about the limitation. Because India's electricity grid is still heavily dependent on coal, a battery electric car in India saves approximately 20% fewer lifecycle CO2 emissions compared to a petrol or diesel vehicle of equivalent size. That is significantly lower than the 60-70% savings seen in countries with cleaner grids like France or Norway.

The environmental benefit of EVs in India will increase substantially as the grid gets cleaner. India added a record 44 GW of solar and 6 GW of wind capacity in FY2026 alone. As renewable energy's share of the grid increases, the same EV becomes progressively greener every year without any modification.

The air quality benefit is more immediate and more local. Zero tailpipe emissions mean less PM2.5 and NOx in the streets where people actually breathe. For Delhi — where vehicular pollution accounts for 39% of PM2.5 — even an imperfect EV is better than a petrol vehicle at the point of use.

### 3.3 Policy Is Getting Serious

The Delhi EV Policy 2026 is a more serious document than the 2020 version. Where the earlier policy focused mainly on purchase subsidies, the 2026 policy introduces infrastructure mandates, deadlines, and institutional accountability. By November 2026, only BS-VI, CNG, or electric goods vehicles will be permitted to enter Delhi — a hard mandate, not a suggestion.

The PM E-Drive scheme is funding 6,130 electric buses under depot electrification, with Rs. 320 crore allocated just for charging infrastructure at bus depots. This signals a shift from passenger EV subsidies toward public transport electrification, which has far greater per-vehicle environmental impact.

